Input: "One of the most frequent causes of air travel delays in the past two decades has been thunderstorms. During the evening, when clouds have formed over populated areas, people often turn on their air conditioners or heating units. In many homes, the air conditioning unit actually exhausts into the outside air instead of pulling it from inside the house into the unit. Heating units do not expel outside air. During the summer months, some homes use the air conditioner almost constantly so that the air flowing out is hot. In the evening, when many residents turn on their units, a rush of hot outside air into the surrounding area can alter the temperature, causing the onset of a local thunderstorm. This is a relatively new problem that affects fewer than 10 percent of all weather delay cases, but it is becoming more common as more houses and businesses use air conditioning units during the early evening. The problem may be reduced by using exhaust air conditioners (those that exhaust air back inside), by installing "air conditioner exhaust" valves so that hot exhaust air cannot be released into the surrounding neighborhood, and by installing air conditioning units in homes with vents that draw air from the outside.
Weather delay information is supplied by the FAA's Air Traffic Control System Command Center that gathers and processes weather information from national weather satellites and the ground stations of airports, weather stations and air traffic control towers. All aircraft must abide by weather minima (lowest practical visibility) that are based on conditions at a nearby airport. Delays occur both at airports and along weather delimitation routes (between airports). Weather information not only includes a report of visibility and ceiling height but whether turbulence is encountered in the vicinity. These weather delay factors may cause planes on landing approaches to abort their attempts and return to the gate. To further complicate things, visibility may not decrease suddenly to the point that aircraft cannot land when a new patch of clouds moves over an airport. Instead, the air may slowly decrease until the aircraft is unable to continue flying through the clouds. Under these conditions, the airliner may descend because of loss of visibility and attempt to land on another runway.
